results.title: SpaceX closes record-breaking first half of 2023 with Starlink launch
results.summary: SpaceX’s last launch of the first half of 2023 is set for this Friday, June 23, carrying 56 Starlink v1.5 satellites. Liftoff is scheduled to occur at 9:57 AM EDT (13:57 UTC) from Space Launch Complex 40 (SLC-40) at Cape Canaveral Space Force Station in Florida. A backup launch attempt is available on the same day 98 minutes later.

results.title: Ship 25 begins engine testing as Starship launch pad work continues
results.summary: Two months after Starship’s first integrated test flight, engine testing is already underway for Ship 25, the ship that will fly on the second launch of Starship. At the same time, SpaceX is approaching the final stretch of completing the foundation work needed at the orbital launch mount (OLM) from where Super Heavy and Starship are set to lift off again no earlier than August. Ship 25 conducted a Spin Prime test on Wednesday.

results.title: Indonesia’s Satria-1 deploys solar panels ahead of geostationary trip
results.summary: Indonesia’s Satria-1 broadband satellite deployed its solar panels after launching on a SpaceX Falcon 9 to geosynchronous transfer orbit over the weekend, manufacturer Thales Alenia Space said June 19.

results.title: Launch Roundup – ULA to launch NROL-68; SpaceX to launch back-to-back Starlink missions
results.summary: In what will be a quiet week for orbital launches, Rocket Lab launched its first suborbital Electron mission; SpaceX launched the Satria satellite to geostationary transfer orbit; China launched the Shiyan 25 payload to a Sun-synchronous low-Earth orbit; the United Launch Alliance (ULA) will launch the penultimate Delta IV Heavy on the NROL-68 mission; and SpaceX will launch two Starlink missions.

results.title: Space Force Assigns SpaceX & ULA New Security Missions
results.summary: The US Space Force launch procurement office has announced that an additional 12 missions have been assigned to SpaceX and United Launch Alliance (ULA) under the National Security Space Launch Phase 2 contract.

results.title: SpaceX, Blue Origin, others highlighted in new NASA low-Earth orbit partnerships
results.summary: On June 15, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) announced its intention to partner with seven U.S. aerospace companies in order to advance human spaceflight and the commercial low-Earth orbit economy.

results.title: NASA Partners With SpaceX, Blue Origin, Sierra Space + 4 Others For Future Commercial Space Capabilities

Falcon 9 is lofting 72 payloads of varying sizes and purposes into a Sun-synchronous orbit. The launch occurred at 2:35 PDT (21:35 UTC).

results.title: Investing in Space: Here are the rockets chasing to compete with SpaceX’s Falcon 9
results.summary: No rocket has been better-described as a “workhorse” than SpaceX’s Falcon 9. Historically a term reserved for the likes of ULA’s Delta II (now retired) or Russia’s Soyuz (now unavailable) or China’s Long March (also unavailable), the blistering pace of Falcon 9 missions has seen the company blow past 200 launches to date, and become the staple of the Western market.

results.title: NASA concerned Starship problems will delay Artemis 3
results.summary: NASA has growing concerns that the lunar lander version of SpaceX’s Starship vehicle will not be ready in time for the Artemis 3 mission in late 2025, given the amount of work needed to get the vehicle ready.

results.title: NASA, SpaceX Launch Solar Arrays, Cargo to Space Station
results.summary: Following a successful launch of NASA’s SpaceX 28th commercial resupply services mission, two new solar arrays, science investigations, and supplies are on their way to the International Space Station.
